Anonymous Sat 26 Mar 2022 04:54:53 No.46446071 Report
Quoted By: >>46446710
>>46445478
This will be rambling.

One of the best tips I can give you is to go into each writing session with a purpose.
I didn't say inspiration or motivation.
Let's take what I was working on tonight. It's the first of at least two, maybe three smut scenes.
I knew this scene was when certain story beats would hit and earlier hints would combine to form a bigger mystery. I have a clue from a previous scene that I have to include. I have two or three hints I have to foreshadow.
So when I decide to save that file tonight, I'll also have a good idea of something else I need to mull over.
Even if you have a very straightforward and linear plot, it is a puzzle.

Or we could look at a backburnered piece I have that will take place in a frontier-ish American setting. I know the next scene will introduce a character that eventually links the MC to the waifur.
It's not ambitious, and like the other story will close out in under 50k words. Maybe half that.

But notice what I'm telling you in a roundabout way?
Every scene is a story in and of itself. It has an opening, some movement where the situation changes, and then a resolution that does one of a few things. You introduce or refine goals, introduce or refine motivations, or introduce or refine conflicts.
Think of your arcs/beats as a series of "...and then..." statements. It's not an outline, but having some overview along with a roughed out character sheet can help you put together random ideas into a coherent story.
90% of your work is in the planning/notes and the editing. First drafts are easy. Last words are fucking hard and require discipline, not inspiration or motivation.
Oh, they help, but don't depend on them.

You can make your first real story a longer one if you accidentally discover how to write beats into scenes and scenes into chapters.
Else, read up on basic structure. Like I gave examples of above, think a bit about what you want to happen.
As you exercise you mind that way, the bits will come to you.

GOOD MORNING SIRS!
